Trump and the Economy
New York—Financial markets have finally come to their senses, realizing that Trump is indeed the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public statements from this most powerful global figure, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, until now, investors have assumed that Trump only talks the talk but doesn't walk the walk.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies beneficial to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that eventually, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies remain within bounds.
This assumption was somewhat validated during Trump's first year in office, a period when economic growth and corporate profit expectations—thanks to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation—resulted in a standout performance by the stock market.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, especially in the final months.
Despite corporate profits increasing by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated heavily for most of the year and is now sharply declining.
Currently, various indices are in a correction phase (i.e., down 10% from recent highs), and the tech stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increased volatility in financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and brought an already near-full employment economy to a climax.
By February, concerns that inflation would rise above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first flight to safety in 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war with China and other important U.S. trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but they are now reaching new heights.
The recent U.S. actions toward China seem to be preparing for a full-blown trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weakened growth along with increased inflation).
After all, Trump is prepared to restrict foreign direct investment and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of the labor supply in the context of an aging population and increasing skill mismatches.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump continuously criticized companies' hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially tech companies, which are already facing widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been hit by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have pushed up short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The U.S. restart of sanctions against Iran pushed up oil prices, and then the U.S. government canceled exemptions and intimidated Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of American energy companies could not hold up.
Moreover, excessive oil price fluctuations are detrimental to both producers and consumers, as they hinder wise investment and consumption decisions.
Even worse, it is now clear that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts flowed to corporate sectors, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in U.S. and global stock markets is Trump's own words and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-blown trade war with China (although he recently reached a "ceasefire" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in spring 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became a nervous wreck this month when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates, while hinting that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the relatively hawkish stance of the Federal Reserve is a reaction to Trump's criticism of it.
Facing hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to signal that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, after Congress refused to fund his useless wall on the Mexican border, Trump decided to shut down the federal government partially.
This move put the market into a quasi-panic state, and soon after the government shutdown, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn a market correction into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the markets.
He claimed that Trump had no plans to fire Powell and that the U.S. fiscal situation was sound — which precisely highlighted the question of whether the situation was actually sound.
Recent internal personnel changes within the government, which may not affect economic decision-making, have also caused concern in the market.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and Trump's cabinet will no longer have any sane individuals.
What remains will be all economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead blindly.
Currently, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new cold war is highly likely to lead to deglobalization, disrupting global supply chains, but the tech industry will be the first to suffer, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO when the European economy and politics are unstable.
Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign's relationship with Russia is the Damocles' sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Now, Trump is Dr. Strangelove of the financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in mutually assured economic destruction.
Nowadays, the market has recognized this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising sharply.
